My finance took me here when we had been at our 6th month dating period. I know! So extravagant for a 6th month thing. But that's how lucky I am to have found such a guy. Unfortunately, he hadn't been feeling well but toughed it out enough so that we ate. And did we eat! I wish I had better pictures, but at the time I didn't know how to manually adjust the focus and lighting om my camera so please excuse the suckiness of the pics. Anyhoo, I'll tell you all the dishes were excellent but what I still remember after all this time were two dishes in particular and would go back to taste them again. The first was a crispy egg salad thing. The egg was cooked so perfectly, just the way I like it with a crispy panko-type breading on the outside, I almost swallowed the whole thing whole. I mean the inside was just runny enough that I wanted to lick every morsel off my fork. The salad underneath was well-seasoned and tasted fresh. I believe there was little bits of crispy pork belly, but I'm wondering if I'm meshing that with the actual pork belly dish that my man got during another course. Haha. The second delicious thing was the lemon cake dessert. My man got the chocolate souffle everyone Yelps about, but really the lemony goodness of my dessert was to die for. It was sweet and tart and fresh and warm and cool all at the same time. I have never had such a delicious lemon dessert in my entire life. Yay life!

Food was good, not great. Service was stuffy. Location was terrible, we were squished against a wall, next to a little cutout cubby hole where the servers get table extras like flatware. Definitely overrated. Nothing special about the interior design. GD did not leave me feeling dazzled.

What an Experience! I have never been to a restaurant like this! My husband and I went here about a year and a half ago for our wedding anniversary. I wish I could go every year. The menu is exquisite! The Service is Impeccable! I ordered from the menu and my husband asked the server to "surprise me..." I would totally recommend to have your server surprise you! I wish I remembered what we had for dinner! And they always serve an "amuse bouche" (did I spell that correctly?) anyway, it was so wonderful the next morning!!!! You definitely need reservations and about 3 hours set aside for your Gary Danko experience. Totally one of the things to add to your bucket list! I hope to be back soon!

With all the hype and hooplah for GDs, I must say that this place was about what I expected it to be. The service was top notch, as it should be, for what you are paying and being a Michelin star restaurant. The food was also amazing, some better than others. So since I'm already here, I'm gonna ball it out and select the 5 course meal, even though it was presumptuous of me. My friends and I were lucky enough to be seated right away in the private dining room. After the waiter spend A LOT of time explaining the menu and what his favorites are, as difficult as it was, we made out decision. My first course was the fried poached egg with truffles. This was seriously the best dish of ALL TIME, my favorite of the night. It was ammaazzing! It was a perfectly poached egg that was flash fried for a crispy outside over bed of mushrooms and veggies. When you cut into the egg, the yolk runs into the rest of the dish and blends well into the sauce and truffle. I will come back here JUST for this! My second course I got the lobster risotto. This was pretty heavy and can be a meal on its own. This was actually nothing exceptional but was just a very well prepared risotto. There wasn't a wow factor that I would expect for GD, other than the fact that it had a lot of pieces of lobster. I wouldn't order this again. My third course was the roasted pork belly. This was also just about what I expected. The meat was well prepared and flavorful. It was separated from the pork belly fat which was on the other side of the plate. All the flavors complimented each other well. I have to admit that by the time I received this dish, I was pretty full so I'm sure the pork actually tasted better than what I experienced due to a full tummy. My fourth course was the cheese platter. This is a must get. The cheese cart itself is just amazing and which ever one you choose, you'll end up picking a winner anyway. All the cheeses were delicious and finger licking good. My fifth course was the warm buttery croissant with apples. At first sight, it didn't look as impressive as the souffle, which I forced myself not to order but to try something new. However, after a bite, the chewy texture and perfect sweetness totally made up for it. It looked small but don't be deceived, it was more than enough to share with even 2 others. As for my friend's plates that I got to taste, the seared scallop was very buttery and delicious that just melts in your mouth. The seared ahi tuna was good and very clean. The passion fruit dessert was super light and fluffy ( I would definitely get it again). The souffle is also super light and yummy with the perfect amount of chocolate-ness. It wasn't dark that it was bitter but it wasn't too sweet either. Bottom line, having been to Fleur de Lys, I would pick them over GD. Granted the ambiance is quiet different and this feels a lot fancier, the food winner, I would have to say ,is Fleur de Lys. However, compared to One Market, GD is a clear winner. For all the hype, it doesn't disappoint. Although the food didn't disappoint, I did wish I was a little bit more wowed by them.

I actually said good night to this guy, and straight up looked and ignored me. Hope chef danko will do something about this guy.

My wife & my review = 4 stars With all the hype and 2+ month waiting list for this restaurant, we had VERY HIGH expectations and was REALLY looking forward to experiencing what everyone else has raved about on here. Unfortunately, our experience here fell a little short... We pull up to the front of the restaurant at 9:15pm (reservations were for 9:30pm). Valet doesn't come to our car so we circle around the block again, this time, I stop, roll down my window and wait. One of the valet guys was nice enough to yell "follow me for a parking spot really close". Sure enough, 4 cars away, he pulls out a customers car and lets us park. Cool, saves us $11 in valet costs. As soon as we give them our name, we get seated and menu's given to us. First impression, the dining room is small and cramped! Maybe 15 or less tables? Our table was within arms length of the tables to the left and right of us. I could've seriously eaten off of the guys plate to the right of me if I wanted! lol With that said, we could hear everything our neighbors were talking about (snooty older rich people bragging about how much money they spent on this and that, etc). We sat there for 15 minutes, then some one asked if we knew what we wanted to drink. Another 15 minutes passed and some one else asks if we were ready to order. Ummm... no introductions, no "thank you for visiting us today, what brings you to our restaurant?", nothing! Once we told the server this was our first time, and asked how the courses work, wine pairings, etc, then we started getting the service we were expecting. Chris was our server for the evening and he did his best to make it up to us. He explained the menu, portion sizes, recommendations, how foods were cooked, etc. I ended up going with the 3 course with wine pairings while my wife got the prefixed 5 course spring menu with the recommended wine pairings. We basically shared everything. Appetizers: * Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frise and Pancetta = Beautifully cooked, crispy yet delicate, and a great starter * Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Asparagus and Peas = BEST risotto I've eaten. Lobster and shrimp were fresh and crunchy and the risotto was perfectly cooked. Fish & Seafood: * Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon = Portion was smaller than I expected but the lobster was perfectly cooked. The puree and trumpet mushrooms were a nice touch to the dish. * Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers and Mustard Sauce = Nice combination of flavors but nothing really stood out on this dish. Salmon would've fallen flat if it didn't have the other fixings/ingredients. If anything, this dish was average Meat & Gamebirds: * Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Roasted Pepper-Eggplant Marmalade and Soy-Mustard Glaze (ordered medium rare) = They gave my wife a butter knife to cut the beef. It was more of a sawing motion because you really had to work at it to cut a slice to eat. Cooked nicely but either the cut was a bit tough for a filet, or we needed an actual steak knife to get through it. Either way, it was a big disappointment and definitely not 5 star quality. * Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Green Garlic Puree and Roasted Grapes = BEST cooked duck I've eaten! Cooked medium rare, the duck came sliced from the kitchen and almost look like a really nice filet of beef, but instead, it was duck! Very tender cut, beautiful flavors, and just an overall GREAT dish. Cheese Cart: We shared this and glad we did. Chris told us that if we were to both have the cheese cart as one of our courses, it would come out to a half a pound of cheese. They have cheeses for all types of people and we basically got everything that we've tried before and was VERY happy! Chris was nice enough to give us a sample of other cheeses on the cart. Dessert: Baked Chocolate Souffle with Two Sauces = Light and fluffy and definitely fulfills your sweet needs after a meal. Wine Pairings: PERFECT...! Although, the snooty people next to us were constantly trying to "test" the sommelier. Just shut up, eat, drink and enjoy your dinner already! JEEEZ! So as you can see, there were some high lights, and there were some flops. We expected this place to be one of the best 5 places we've ever eaten at but unfortunately, it didn't quite make our list. With the poor service in the beginning, to the annoying neighbors that were too close, and all the courses not giving us foodgasms, we can only recommend this place to try just once if you're a foodie like us.

Obviously Gary Danko is a great restaurant. Obviously the one-star rating I've assigned is an anomaly. It represents our rather unpleasant 40 minutes in the place; your experience would most likely be as rapturous as those described in the great majority of reviews here, but I am writing to issue a caveat for the unwary. We had a 9:00 reservation on a nondescript Sunday night. We would have preferred something earlier, but 9:00 was the best we could do with the lead time we had. We arrived about 8:45 and were advised, not unexpectedly, that our table was not ready. We were led to the bar, which at that time had no available stools. We stood among a small herd of our fellow heel-coolers until two stools opened up at about 8:55. We sat and ordered a drink. By 9:10 the bar area was backed up to the door with others waiting for their reservations to be honored. By 9:15, I was ready to leave. We had been elbowed, jostled, batted hither and yon by the madding crowd. The volume of the attendant hubbub was just this side of deafening. By 9:20, I had paid for the drinks and announced our intention to leave. The hostess, aghast, asked me if I'd speak to the manager, which I did. She was unpersuasive; we left at about 9:25 amid pleas that "several tables were paying." I'd believe our experience was unusual except that we were not the only ones subjected to the uncomfortable wait. I was left with the distinct impression from this one-time sampling that the restaurant routinely overbooks, depending on its apparently well-deserved culinary reputation to elicit Job-like patience from its eager clientele. If the experience you expect from an establishment affiliated with Relais et Châteaux includes red carpet treatment from the moment you walk in the door, I'd suggest that you avoid Gary Danko, or at the very least, make it a high priority to score an early evening reservation.

Of course, I used my birthday as an excuse to try Gary Danko. It was nice to be treated like the princess for a night! GD is the perfect place to be pampered! We had made 8:00pm reservations and unfortunately upon our arrival, had to wait a good 15 minutes before we could be seated. From start to finish Gary Danko is like a show. Right when you step out of the car, you are escorted into a dark space with blacked out windows, almost like you are VIP going into a secret location. Inside it is dimly lit with the bar being a straight shot from the door. Beautiful flower arrangements and white linen table clothes make the room comfy and quaint. The wait staff here is very intuitive. Each dish they bring out to you is like a dance. They give each other the knowing eye and proceed to place your plate down in a in sync manner. Suave. The menu was packed full of choices. Unlike other fine dining places, you can choose your own 3, 4, 5 course meal in any order and in any combination. I chose the Crab Soup Appetizer, the Lobster, and the Crème Brule for dessert. I had to cancel the cheese course because after the lobster, I was bursting at the seams. They were nice enough to cancel it without making a big deal and were very understanding. They didn't charge us either (some places are mean like that). My other friends had the quail, scallops, and the lamb. We also shared the chocolate soufflés and the peach flambé, which is prepared tableside and serves 2 (charge you for 2 as well, hidden charge). The waiter reminded me of a game show host. He was very animated and very friendly. He remarkably put on a great show for us, explaining every detail he was doing. Thankfully nothing caught on fire except my heart when I dug into the desserts. The peaches were so ripe and fresh. Amazing! For the birthday girl, they brought out a little tray of small bite size cookies for a tasting. They brought out a chocolate mouse type of cake with a candle on it for me. Made me feel all warm and tingly inside (it was probably the soufflé) The entire meal was an experience and a fantastic one. The food was amazing and the wait staff were very friendly and knowledgeable. Great place for a special occasion. Bill came out to over $1000 for 4. Be careful what you decide to splurge on! They do valet and will add it on to the food bill.

I've been here twice. First time was 3 years ago (when foi gras was still legal in CA) and second time was a year ago. It was much better the first time I visited. I'm not sure when I last visited it was just by chance that it didn't taste as good or the quality has decreased. Meal is still consider amazing (hence 4 stars) but none of the dish really stood out to me and were not super memorable.

    With all the hype and hooplah for GDs, I must say that this place was about what I expected it to be.  The service was top notch, as it should be, for what you are paying and being a Michelin star restaurant.  The food was also amazing, some better than others.

    So since I'm already here, I'm gonna ball it out and select the 5 course meal, even though it was presumptuous of me.  My friends and I were lucky enough to be seated right away in the private dining room.  After the waiter spend A LOT of time explaining the menu and what his favorites are, as difficult as it was, we made out decision.  

    My first course was the fried poached egg with truffles.  This was seriously the best dish of ALL TIME, my favorite of the night.  It was ammaazzing!  It was a perfectly poached egg that was flash fried for a crispy outside over bed of mushrooms and veggies.  When you cut into the egg, the yolk runs into the rest of the dish and blends well into the sauce and truffle.  I will come back here JUST for this!

    My second course I got the lobster risotto.  This was pretty heavy and can be a meal on its own.  This was actually nothing exceptional but was just a very well prepared risotto.  There wasn't a wow factor that I would expect for GD, other than the fact that it had a lot of pieces of lobster.  I wouldn't order this again.

    My third course was the roasted pork belly.  This was also just about what I expected.  The meat was well prepared and flavorful.  It was separated from the pork belly fat which was on the other side of the plate.  All the flavors complimented each other well.  I have to admit that by the time I received this dish, I was pretty full so I'm sure the pork actually tasted better than what I experienced due to a full tummy.

    My fourth course was the cheese platter.  This is a must get.  The cheese cart itself is just amazing and which ever one you choose, you'll end up picking a winner anyway.  All the cheeses were delicious and finger licking good.

    My fifth course was the warm buttery croissant with apples.  At first sight, it didn't look as impressive as the souffle, which I forced myself not to order but to try something new.  However, after a bite, the chewy texture and perfect sweetness totally made up for it.  It looked small but don't be deceived, it was more than enough to share with even 2 others.

    As for my friend's plates that I got to taste, the seared scallop was very buttery and delicious that just melts in your mouth.  The seared ahi tuna was good and very clean.  The passion fruit dessert was super light and fluffy ( I would definitely get it again).  The souffle is also super light and yummy with the perfect amount of chocolate-ness.  It wasn't dark that it was bitter but it wasn't too sweet either.

    Bottom line, having been to Fleur de Lys, I would pick them over GD.  Granted the ambiance is quiet different and this feels a lot fancier, the food winner, I would have to say ,is Fleur de Lys.  However, compared to One Market, GD is a clear winner.  For all the hype, it doesn't disappoint.  Although the food didn't disappoint, I did wish I was a little bit more wowed by them.

    1 check-in

    My wife & my review = 4 stars

    With all the hype and 2+ month waiting list for this restaurant, we had VERY HIGH expectations and was REALLY looking forward to experiencing what everyone else has raved about on here. Unfortunately, our experience here fell a little short...

    We pull up to the front of the restaurant at 9:15pm (reservations were for 9:30pm). Valet doesn't come to our car so we circle around the block again, this time, I stop, roll down my window and wait. One of the valet guys was nice enough to yell "follow me for a parking spot really close". Sure enough, 4 cars away, he pulls out a customers car and lets us park. Cool, saves us $11 in valet costs.

    As soon as we give them our name, we get seated and menu's given to us. First impression, the dining room is small and cramped! Maybe 15 or less tables? Our table was within arms length of the tables to the left and right of us. I could've seriously eaten off of the guys plate to the right of me if I wanted! lol With that said, we could hear everything our neighbors were talking about (snooty older rich people bragging about how much money they spent on this and that, etc). We sat there for 15 minutes, then some one asked if we knew what we wanted to drink. Another 15 minutes passed and some one else asks if we were ready to order. Ummm... no introductions, no "thank you for visiting us today, what brings you to our restaurant?", nothing! Once we told the server this was our first time, and asked how the courses work, wine pairings, etc, then we started getting the service we were expecting. Chris was our server for the evening and he did his best to make it up to us. He explained the menu, portion sizes, recommendations, how foods were cooked, etc. I ended up going with the 3 course with wine pairings while my wife got the prefixed 5 course spring menu with the recommended wine pairings. We basically shared everything.

    Appetizers:
    * Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frise and Pancetta = Beautifully cooked, crispy yet delicate, and a great starter
    * Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Asparagus and Peas = BEST risotto I've eaten. Lobster and shrimp were fresh and crunchy and the risotto was perfectly cooked.

    Fish & Seafood:
    * Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Puree, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon = Portion was smaller than I expected but the lobster was perfectly cooked. The puree and trumpet mushrooms were a nice touch to the dish.
    * Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers and Mustard Sauce = Nice combination of flavors but nothing really stood out on this dish. Salmon would've fallen flat if it didn't have the other fixings/ingredients. If anything, this dish was average

    Meat & Gamebirds:
    * Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Roasted Pepper-Eggplant Marmalade and Soy-Mustard Glaze (ordered medium rare) = They gave my wife a butter knife to cut the beef. It was more of a sawing motion because you really had to work at it to cut a slice to eat. Cooked nicely but either the cut was a bit tough for a filet, or we needed an actual steak knife to get through it. Either way, it was a big disappointment and definitely not 5 star quality.
    * Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Green Garlic Puree and Roasted Grapes = BEST cooked duck I've eaten! Cooked medium rare, the duck came sliced from the kitchen and almost look like a really nice filet of beef, but instead, it was duck! Very tender cut, beautiful flavors, and just an overall GREAT dish.

    Cheese Cart:
    We shared this and glad we did. Chris told us that if we were to both have the cheese cart as one of our courses, it would come out to a half a pound of cheese. They have cheeses for all types of people and we basically got everything that we've tried before and was VERY happy! Chris was nice enough to give us a sample of other cheeses on the cart.

    Dessert:
    Baked Chocolate Souffle with Two Sauces = Light and fluffy and definitely fulfills your sweet needs after a meal.

    Wine Pairings:
    PERFECT...! Although, the snooty people next to us were constantly trying to "test" the sommelier. Just shut up, eat, drink and enjoy your dinner already! JEEEZ!

    So as you can see, there were some high lights, and there were some flops. We expected this place to be one of the best 5 places we've ever eaten at but unfortunately, it didn't quite make our list. With the poor service in the beginning, to the annoying neighbors that were too close, and all the courses not giving us foodgasms, we can only recommend this place to try just once if you're a foodie like us.

    6/3/2014

    Obviously Gary Danko is a great restaurant. Obviously the one-star rating I've assigned is an anomaly. It represents our rather unpleasant 40 minutes in the place; your experience would most likely be as rapturous as those described in the great majority of reviews here, but I am writing to issue a caveat for the unwary.

    We had a 9:00 reservation on a nondescript Sunday night. We would have preferred something earlier, but 9:00 was the best we could do with the lead time we had. We arrived about 8:45 and were advised, not unexpectedly, that our table was not ready. We were led to the bar, which at that time had no available stools. We stood among a small herd of our fellow heel-coolers until two stools opened up at about 8:55. We sat and ordered a drink. By 9:10 the bar area was backed up to the door with others waiting for their reservations to be honored. By 9:15, I was ready to leave. We had been elbowed, jostled, batted hither and yon by the madding crowd. The volume of the attendant hubbub was just this side of deafening. By 9:20, I had paid for the drinks and announced our intention to leave. The hostess, aghast, asked me if I'd speak to the manager, which I did. She was unpersuasive; we left at about 9:25 amid pleas that "several tables were paying."

    I'd believe our experience was unusual except that we were not the only ones subjected to the uncomfortable wait. I was left with the distinct impression from this one-time sampling that the restaurant routinely overbooks, depending on its apparently well-deserved culinary reputation to elicit Job-like patience from its eager clientele.

    If the experience you expect from an establishment affiliated with Relais et Châteaux includes red carpet treatment from the moment you walk in the door, I'd suggest that you avoid Gary Danko, or at the very least, make it a high priority to score an early evening reservation.

    Of course, I used my birthday as an excuse to try Gary Danko. It was nice to be treated like the princess for a night! GD is the perfect place to be pampered! We had made 8:00pm reservations and unfortunately upon our arrival, had to wait a good 15 minutes before we could be seated.

    From start to finish Gary Danko is like a show. Right when you step out of the car, you are escorted into a dark space with blacked out windows, almost like you are VIP going into a secret location. Inside it is dimly lit with the bar being a straight shot from the door. Beautiful flower arrangements and white linen table clothes make the room comfy and quaint. The wait staff here is very intuitive. Each dish they bring out to you is like a dance. They give each other the knowing eye and proceed to place your plate down in a in sync manner. Suave. The menu was packed full of choices. Unlike other fine dining places, you can choose your own 3, 4, 5 course meal in any order and in any combination.

    I chose the Crab Soup Appetizer, the Lobster, and the Crème Brule for dessert. I had to cancel the cheese course because after the lobster, I was bursting at the seams. They were nice enough to cancel it without making a big deal and were very understanding. They didn't charge us either (some places are mean like that). My other friends had the quail, scallops, and the lamb. We also shared the chocolate soufflés and the peach flambé, which is prepared tableside and serves 2 (charge you for 2 as well, hidden charge).

    The waiter reminded me of a game show host. He was very animated and very friendly.  He remarkably put on a great show for us, explaining every detail he was doing. Thankfully nothing caught on fire except my heart when I dug into the desserts. The peaches were so ripe and fresh. Amazing! For the birthday girl, they brought out a little tray of small bite size cookies for a tasting. They brought out a chocolate mouse type of cake with a candle on it for me. Made me feel all warm and tingly inside (it was probably the soufflé)

    The entire meal was an experience and a fantastic one. The food was amazing and the wait staff were very friendly and knowledgeable. Great place for a special occasion.

    Bill came out to over $1000 for 4. Be careful what you decide to splurge on! They do valet and will add it on to the food bill.
